paragraphs.text: You have to practice even, maybe especially, when it hurts.
paragraphs.name: 003f

paragraphs.text: You have to know what you are before you can figure out what you want to do.
paragraphs.name: 55b5
7fca
paragraphs.text: This doesn’t mean you have to be a jack of all trades, but you must become a master of some. For example, all the professional writers I know are good at more than one thing. One is a great publicist. Another is really smart at leadership. Another is a fantastic speaker.
You have to become a student long before you get to be a master.
paragraphs.name: f48b
f5f8
paragraphs.text: In my case, I spent too long waiting for someone to call me a writer before I was willing to act like one. Now I’ve learned that clarity comes with action. We must perform our way into professionalism. We must first call ourselves what we want to become, and then get to the work of mastery.
Either way, you must develop your own portfolio.
paragraphs.name: 73f4

paragraphs.text: Either way, you must develop your own portfolio.
paragraphs.name: 73f4

paragraphs.text: Sure, there are ways to expedite the process, but it is still a process. And for me, I didn’t start to succeed as a writer until I began shifting my attention away from the results. When I began to mimic the process of professionals instead of just chasing their success, that’s when I started to see real results.

If you want to be a pro in your field, you’re going to have to break this terrible amateur habit of looking at what people have without paying attention to what they did to get it. Chasing the results without understanding the process will lead to short-lived success, if not outright failure.
paragraphs.name: 90e8
833c
paragraphs.text: 2. Amateurs want to arrive. Pros want to get better.
I recently spoke with a best-selling author who has sold tens of millions of books. Do you know when his career started to really take off? It was when he wrote his 125th book at age 45.
paragraphs.name: 1ccd

paragraphs.text: You have to care about legacy more than ego.
paragraphs.name: 077e
4b0c
paragraphs.text: I recently spoke with a creative professional in New York who makes a living as both a fine artist and a photographer. He knows, as all professionals do,that all our skills complement each other and, frankly, relieve us from putting too much pressure on ourselves to be the world’s best at any one thing.

This doesn’t mean you have to be a jack of all trades, but you must become a master of some. For example, all the professional writers I know are good at more than one thing. One is a great publicist. Another is really smart at leadership. Another is a fantastic speaker.
paragraphs.name: 7fca

paragraphs.text: This is so true. When I left my job as a journalist to become a teacher, I figured my writing would suffer. I was able to write four to five hours most days as a reporter. I now log about an hour each day.

f1293abf9e63.title: The vein running through all 7 is dedication to a direction.

paragraphs.text: The vein running through all 7 is dedication to a direction. Today’s YPs are paralyzed by social media’s showcase of each craft or venture they could be pursuing. Jeff’s nailed it here… dedicate yourself to a direction, build something, then use it as a data point or springboard if you feel you should pivot later.
